properties.incident: Report about of the humanitarian condition in the besieged cities, Talbisah and Al Rastan 27/9/2011- 1/10/2011
properties.incident translation: Report about of the humanitarian condition in the besieged cities, Talbisah and Al Rastan 27/9/2011- 1/10/2011
properties.description:
*The humanitarian condition in the besieged cities, Talbisah and Al Rastan;
the suburbs of Homs*

* 27/9/2011- 1/10/2011*****

** **

*Talbisah and Rastan: Living conditions in the two cities:*****

The two cities are currently being subjected to violent blockade by the
Syrian army and security forces. All Entrances and exits from the city are
closed as well as the sub-ways and agricultural roads. Also, the main
Homs-Hama road is blocked.****

Electricity, water and all communications have been cut off for 6 days now.
The two cities are experiencing deathly shortages of food and medicine and
diesel to operate machinery. Testimonies of heavy bombing on the main bread
factory have also been reported leaving civilians in dire situations. There
are extreme shortages in medicine and baby formulas due to acts of vandalism
and occupation by the Syrian Army on all pharmacies and emergency care
centers that are now utilized by the Syrian Army as sniper stations to shoot
down any civilian walking in the street. All schools have been shut down.***
*

Reports of over 200 bombs over the city of Talbisah; 100 of those bombs have
hit the historical sight of an old castle and the rest all over the city. 30
homes have been completely demolished and 60 homes in non living conditions.
60 water tanks have been shot at leaving the entire city with no water on
both cities.****

All residential homes in the eastern parts of Rastan have been attacked
which forced the civilians to move into the down town areas, however, still
not safe from the heavy bombing for the past 4 days now where clashes
between the Syrian army and the defected army personnel.****

** **

 ****

*Vandalism and loitering *****

The Syrian Security forces have damaged and vandalized all shops in the
Al-Karaj shopping center in Rastan as well as all shops on the main street
in Talbisah.****

** **

*Arrests, death threats and abductions:*****

Security forces are currently arresting anyone who attempts to deliver any
type of humanitarian and medical assistance to the two cities; one of which
is an old man. In addition to the daily arrests taking place, families in
the two cities are being threatened to have their children killed and hung
should they attempt to demonstrate in the streets again. Current and
accurate death toll is extremely hard to verify due to the blockade however
reports have authenticated 15 names of martyrs four of them women and
children. ****

** **

*Neighboring towns:*****

All towns neighboring Talbisah and Rastan are being subjected to sever
siege, terror, arrests and gunfire****

*Al Ghantu, Ter Maalle, Zafarane, Qunaiterat, Ez Eddin, Farhaniyye, Ghajr,
Dhaheriyye, Der Fool, Ghasbiyye, Makrameyye, Hashmeyye*****

Security checkpoints spread in all entrances and exits of these towns,
snipers deployed in all areas to stop movement****

Security forces waged a wide campaign of arrests in most of these areas, 7
young men from Ez Eddin town were arrested after they were wounded by
snipers bullets, in addition to 8 others from Zafarane, among them a 10
year old child, also in Ghajr town****

A curfew have been imposed in all areas from 7 pm, even in the morning
residents fear to go out of their homes due to the intensive deployment of
snipers****

 ****

*Authenticated names of martyrs during this attack on civilians:*****

*Martyrs of Rastan:*****

1.    Soldier Basheer Mansur****

2.    Lieutenant Ahmad Khalaf****

3.    Soldier Mohammad Hesyan  from Qusayir (killed in Rastan)****

4.    Unknown first name of man from the Errez family****

5.    Abdul-Munem Bahbuh****

6.    Sharif Musa****

7.    Mohammad Fayez Salama****

8.    Abul-Rahim Al-Amer (a doctor)****

9.    Anwar Al-Sheikh Ali****

10.  The child Hadi Al-Haj Yusef****

11.  The child Hafedh Mohammad Hamdan****

12.  Mahmoud Ahmad Al-Ashtar****

13.  Sharif Mousa Errez****

14.  Yusef Al-Ashtar****

15.  Um Ziyad Farazat****

 ****

Massive numbers of martyrs have not been authenticated yet due to the
difficulty of delivery and verification of information.****

** **

 ****

 ****

*Martyrs of Talbisah:*****

1.    Maryam Al-Ghajari (Um Ali)****

2.    Hasan Nasan Addaqa- 20 years old****

3.    Ahmad Abul-Ilah Al-Dhaik  20 years old****

 ****

*Acts of terror and intimidation:*****

Thugs and security forces are aiding the army in launching street wars using
heavy army weapons such as Sheilka, 500 DMs leaving innocent civilians in
cases of frantic cases of panic and desp* *****

** **

properties.incident translation: Report about the situation in Rastan Sunday 2-Oct-2011
properties.description:
*Report about the situation in Rastan Sunday 2-Oct-2011*

*--------------------------------------------------------------*

*Rastan Local Coordination Committee*

*
*

** **

         *Situation on the ground: *

*
*

1.     Gunfire and artillery shells throughout yesterdays night in the
centre of the city ****

2.     Flames and black some rise from all the main street (Al-Thawara
street) in the early morning****

3.     Big number of checkpoints in all main streets of the city, that is;
each checkpoint is 200 meters far from the other****

4.     Big number of residents left their homes and fled ****

5.     Occupation of a lot of homes, looting and damaging them by Shabiha
and #Asaad army****

6.     We receive from military sources that clashes took place between
Asaads forces and the Free Syrian Army at the borders of the city, where
they caused extensive damage for Asaads battalions****

7.     Arrests still continued till the moment without distinguishing
between adults and children ****

8.     Schools are full of detainees who are being transferred in batches to
the air security branch to be tortured ****

9.     20 children were executed yesterday in cold blood, where they were
taken from their homes in pretext of investigation and families were told
that they will be returned back later on, but they were murdered near the
military consumption corporation****

10.  More than 50 tanks headed to Al Houla, in addition, another big number
headed to other cities of Homs****

11.  The international autostrade (Homs-Hama) is still blocked ****

12.  Entrance and exist from Rastan is not allowed ****

** **

         *The humanitarian situation:*

*
*

1.     Electricity and all kinds of communications are completely cut off,
partial cut-off of water****

2.     Residents are unable to move and bring their essential needs****

3.     Big number of remnants of exploded and non exploded shells in streets
and homes, and spread of damage and litter in the streets
which threatens the occurrence and epidemic disease that may kill many
people****

4.     A tightened curfew in the city that threatens everybody moves in the
streets****

5.     Loss of heart , diabetes medications and big number of drugs as a
result of burning pharmacies****

6.     Ration materials began to finish in the sixth day of siege, frozen
food become rot****

7.     People are not able to get infants milk and medicines ****

8.     All groceries and their contents have been looted by Shabiha and
security forces and they are preventing delivering ration materials to the
city****

9.     Many families are residing outdoors after their homes were occupied,
and are not being able to reconquest their homes and therefore they are
homeless ****

10.  Gold shops and money were looted by Shabiha and security forces during
inspection ****

properties.incident: Dr. Ali Aqeel & Dr. Nael Al-Dakhil
properties.incident translation: Dr. Ali Aqeel & Dr. Nael Al-Dakhil
properties.description:
Why did criminal Bashar Al-Assad and his gang singled out, as targets
for killing, Dr. Ali Aqeel &amp; Dr. Nael Al-Dakhil?
Both Dr. Ali Aqeel &amp; Dr. Nael Al-Dakhil are participants in dialogues
that took place under this treacherous regime, starting on the 5th of
this month in the hotel of Homs Ambassador. The 2 men took
positions that did not please the servants of the regime which based
on security-intelligence agencies. That is especially true because of
the sensitivity of what each of these 2 men represent in terms of
academic and scientific stature. Also because Dr. Aqeel belongs to a
sect which the regime calculated as being affiliated with it; still
Dr. Aqeel, &amp; during his interview with the Russian delegation,
explained the reality of the situation in the city of Homs, &amp; he was
quoted saying during his meeting with the ambassador: The Baath Party
seized control of every aspect of life in Syria, &amp; that dealing with
the situation with security-based-solution will lead Syria to the
unknown.

properties.incident: Summary of events in Homs on 26/09/2011.
properties.incident translation: Summary of events in Homs on 26/09/2011.
properties.description:
Summary of events in Homs on 26/09/2011.

News from the neighbourhoods:

Around twelve o'clock at night and beyond, deployed forces began to shoot
heavily and randomly as usual around a number of checkpoints, especially
scattered checkpoints on Alqahirah road in Albayada, around Alqalaa (Bab
Alsibaa) and the roundabout of Bab Aldreib in order to scare off the people
and also to harm them. However the sound of gunshots has become part of the
daily routine for the families of Homs

Homs Deir Baalbah, the bullets and bombs that are used against civilians

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AxSXVkPLJfc

Homs Deir Baalbah: With the start of university, tanks and barricades enter
university campuses- The University of Petroleum and Chemical Engineering.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5CntaeZMsCY

This was heard from then, until the early hours of the  morning, the sounds
of war planes in the skies of Homs (the city) in all it's neighborhoods.
And before noon, the checkpoints and armed vehicles that were stationed in
Bab Aldreib neighborhoods and Jub Aljandali began opening heavy, random and
intermittent fire, and this continued for a couple of hours to intimidate
people and pressure them into returning home

And so came out the youth of the revolution from their schools in mass
protests as did Mosa from the Pharaoh

Date: Wed, 27 Jul 2011 16:35:38 +0100
From: 
Subject: Syria updates

Week of Detainees: Raqa
 Today (Tuesday), about 50 detainees on the background of participating in peaceful demonstrations in Raqa started an open hunger strike until they are released

Week of Detainees: Hasakeh
Mohammed Al Harif and Hussain Eiso were battered and detained by the criminal security directly after they left the public prosecutor office in Hasakeh, they were meeting him on behalf of the detainees families that are sitting in front of the Justice Palace. Sami Mohammed Al Fayad, Daham Mohammed Al Fayad and Khalid Nimr Al Musalet were also detained among others during or after the sit in, security cars followed them to arrest them away from the public. 
Aram Faisl Al Badr- 17 year old was detained because he participated in demonstrations, he was asked to report to political security branch in Hasakeh to receive his national ID that was taken earlier.

Week of Detainees, Saida
 people from Saida- Daraa were arrested after raiding the city, the names reported so far are: Walid Majaresh, Nabil Majaresh, Ali Mahamid, Khalil Mohammed Fahd Al Zaeil, Ali Fawzi Al Mahamid


Daraa: Dael
A raiding campaign is taking place now in Dael. Three security buses are entering the Eastern Suburb and three military buses are present on the town's entrances

Speaking via Al-Jazeera, he left over the massacres of citizens and denied the army was fighting armed groups. He claimed Bashar Assad's men were placing weapons and ammunition next to unarmed protesters to make it appear as though they were gunmen at Daraa and Sanamin. Tlass urged his fellow officers to give up protecting the Assad family and instead protect and defend civillians. He was from Homs-Rastan.

properties.description: RT @SyriaTracker: To report crimes in #Syria, you can call and leave a message to either +16504194196 or +390662207294 or +442033184514 #basharcrimes

Seven Syrian citizens sued the Syrian government, they and their family members have been tortured
http://t.co/ZomlM1G

"Plaintiff Hala Abdul Aziz says she learned of the death of her father, Abdul Gafar Abdul Aziz, through a video posted online.
     Abdul Aziz, 50, was killed by snipers on April 22 after "mourners gathered to give a speech about the murders committed by the Syrian security forces during the past month," his daughter says.
     Plaintiff John Doe No. 1 says his brother was also shot to death at a peaceful demonstration after a funeral at a mosque on April 17.
     Plaintiff Sirwan Kajjo says she attended a soccer game in Qamchilei where security forces killed three children on March 12, 2004. The next day, during the children's funeral, security forces killed 34 people who were protesting the Syrian security forces' killings of the day before, Kajjo says.
     Plaintiff Mohammad Al Abdullah says he was imprisoned in Damascus from March to October 2006. He says he was "interrogated for three hours, during which time he was slapped and punched several times and forced to stand blindfolded and handcuffed throughout the entire interrogation."
     The interrogator threatened to whip him and torture him, and prison guards made his cellmate jog until he was unable to walk, and Abdullah "had to carry him to the toilet for the next three days," according to the complaint.
     Plaintiff Abed Al-Hendi says he too was imprisoned in Damascus for criticizing the government online. In prison, he says, he was "routinely beaten and tortured by the guards, which included hitting his face and body with sticks and kicking him."
     John Doe No. 2, a philosophy teacher and human rights advocate, says was repeatedly imprisoned from 1981 to 1998 and from 2003 to 2007, "locked in a one cubic meter dark, airless cell in a humid underground area.""
You can now call to either +16504194196 or +390662207294 or +442033184514 and we will receive your message immediately and add it to the body of evidence collected through Syria Tracker.

properties.incident translation: SYRIA: What they are saying about the protests: IRIN News
properties.description:
SYRIA: What they are saying about the protests

DUBAI, 27 April 2011 (IRIN) - Hundreds of people have reportedly died in unrest in Syria since mid-March, many at the hands of the security forces, leading to growing international condemnation of the use of excessive force by President Bashar al-Assad's government to suppress protests.

 Syrian residents, the government, human rights organizations and international personalities have all spoken out on the situation. Below are excerpts:


 Person one talking to IRIN from Syria:

 "Until now, the situation has not calmed down despite all the changes made by the government and the abolition of the emergency law. People are still demonstrating but not in huge numbers. But in general, Syrians are fearful because they cannot predict what will happen."

 Person two talking to IRIN from Syria:

 "What we see on TV channels is extremely exaggerated. It is only hundreds of people demonstrating here and there. People say some of the footage goes back to incidents that took place in Lebanon in 2008. Syrians are leading a normal life and they are sending their kids to school. Also the country has not witnessed any hike in food prices."

 President Bashar al-Assad: [ http://www.sana.sy/eng/21/2011/04/18/pr-341923.htm ]

 18 April - "Syria is going through a critical stage... there are different components of this stage. There is the conspiracy. There are the reforms and the needs... the blood which has been spilled in Syria has pained us all. It pained the heart of every Syrian. We are sad for the loss of every Syrian and for all those who have been injured... We consider them all martyrs, whether they were civilians, members of the police or the armed forces... The investigation committee is proceeding with its work in order to know the causes of what happened and to identify those responsible and then bring them to account.

 "The Syrian constitution allows for demonstrations, but we do not have a law which regulates the process of demonstrating. This process is a challenge to the police because they are not prepared for such things... There might be a need for restructuring the police in order to cope with the new reforms. One of the tasks of the police is to protect demonstrators and at the same time protect other individuals and public and private property from any attempt at sabotage or undermining people's security."

 Government through the Syrian News Agency [ http://www.sana.sy/eng/29/2011/04/27/343515.htm ]:

 24 April - "A number of foreign media sources continue to spread lies and misdirection about the events in Syria, impersonating people under the guise of so-called eyewitnesses. Ammar Agha, a Syrian surgeon from the town of Jableh, told the Syrian Satellite Channel that one of the callers... impersonated him to tell lies and events that he knows nothing about in Jableh."

 27 April - "Nine policemen of the Internal Security Forces were wounded over the past two days by extremist terrorist groups, raising the number of injuries among the forces' officers since the start of events in Syria to 295."


 Syrian Human Rights Commission: [ http://www.shrc.org/data/aspx/d11/4421.aspx ]

 17 April - "Protests in Homs and the city of Talbisa north of Homs witnessed today the death of several people by the security forces, popular committees and thugs supporting them. The victims were taking part in a peaceful protest calling for freedom during the funeral of some of the victims in Talbisa.

 "Several injuries have also been reported and several hospitals in the city including the Bab Al-Sibaa' Hospital and the Al-Razi Hospital have pleaded for blood donations, while security forces arrested several citizens who rushed to donate much-needed blood to aid the tens of injured who mostly suffer from direct and serious injuries in the head and chest... both Ridwan Al-Smoody and Tareq Zanbo from Latakia have been killed today as the security forces fired at the peaceful demonstrators."

 UN High Commissioner for Human Rights Navi Pillay [ http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=38181&Cr=syria&Cr1= ]:

 25 April - "The international community has repeatedly urged the Syrian government to stop killing its own people, but our calls have gone unheeded. Instead, the government's response has been erratic, with paper reforms followed by violent crackdowns on protesters. Just a few days after the announcement of sweeping and important reforms, we are seeing such disregard for human life by Syrian security forces. The killings must stop immediately.

 The [OHCHR] has received a list naming 76 people who were killed on Friday [22 April] during evidently peaceful marches, but noted that the number may be much higher. It is also looking into the reported killing of at least 13 others in funeral processions on Saturday [23 April]."

 UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon [ http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=38198&Cr=syria&Cr1= ]:

 26 April - "I condemn, utterly, the continuing violence against peaceful demonstrators, most particularly the use of tanks and live fire that have killed and injured hundreds of people. It goes without saying that Syrian authorities have an obligation to protect civilians and respect international human rights. That includes the right to free expression and peaceful assembly."

 Catherine Ashton, EU High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy: [ http://europa.eu/press_room/index_en.htm ]

 23 April - "I condemn the use of brutal force against demonstrators across Syria, which is resulting in high numbers of victims. The Syrian authorities must immediately stop their violent response and fully respect citizens' right to peaceful demonstrations. I deeply regret the death of many protesters on 21 April, and offer my condolences to their families. The killings are appalling and intolerable. All those responsible for these crimes must be brought to justice and held accountable for their actions.

 "I noted President Assad's announcement of three decrees on 20 April, related to the lifting of the state of emergency, abolition of the Higher State Security Court and a right to peaceful protests. However, credible reform can only be measured by real improvements on the ground."

 Human Rights Watch: [ http://reliefweb.int/taxonomy/term/1966 ]

 24 April - "The UN should set up an international inquiry into the fatal shootings by Syria's security forces of peaceful protesters... the inquiry should also examine other human rights violations committed since anti-government protests began in mid-March. The US and European Union should also impose sanctions on Syrian officials who bear responsibility for the use of lethal force against peaceful protesters and the arbitrary detention and torture of hundreds of protesters, as well as request an urgent briefing of the UN Security Council on the spiralling situation in the country.

 "On April 22, Syria's security forces killed at least 76 protesters, and possibly as many as 112, according to lists compiled by local human rights activists. Human Rights Watch interviewed protesters in the towns of Homs, Ezraa, Douma, and Maadamiya, who reported that security forces opened fire on them without warning. On April 23, security forces shot at funeral processions in Barza, Douma, and Ezraa, killing at least 12 additional mourners."

 Amnesty International:  [ www.amnesty.org ]

 26 April - "The UN Security Council must refer the situation in Syria to the Prosecutor of the International Criminal Court. The Syrian government is clearly trying to shatter the will of those peacefully expressing dissent by shelling them, firing on them and locking them up.

 "[Amnesty is calling] for the imposition of a comprehensive arms embargo on Syria and an assets freeze on President Bashar al-Assad and others involved in ordering or perpetrating serious human rights abuses... unarmed Syrians gathering to call for greater freedom have routinely been attacked by security forces firing live ammunition directly into crowds of peaceful demonstrators... violence has since spiralled, with at least 120 people killed on [22 April], until then the bloodiest day so far. Amnesty International has received the names of 393 people killed since protests began."

 The Global Centre for the Responsibility to Protect: [ http://www.globalr2p.org/ ]

 26 April - "The situation is deteriorating and the risk of further atrocities is significant. Over 350 individuals have allegedly been killed since the protests began, at least 120 since Friday [22 April] alone. The security forces have shown no restraint, using live fire ammunition against unarmed protesters. In the southern city of Deraa they are relying on tanks and other heavy weaponry to respond to demonstrations.

 "Reports have emerged from [Deraa] of shelling of residential neighbourhoods and the use of snipers targeting those trying to assist the wounded. Foreign reporters have been banned from entering the country and there are reports that the telephone service has been cut in certain cities, making it difficult to get information out and leading to fears about what the government plans to do hidden from the attention of the world."
